1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:03,650
In this video we are going to learn dual write problem.

2
00:00:03,650 --> 00:00:10,910
Dual write problem occurs when application needs to change data in two different systems, for example

3
00:00:10,910 --> 00:00:13,040
a database and a message queue.

4
00:00:13,070 --> 00:00:18,350
If one of the write fails, it can result in inconsistent state.

5
00:00:19,460 --> 00:00:26,240
This is the typical case when you use a local transactions with each of the external systems operations.

6
00:00:26,600 --> 00:00:33,740
For example, when an application needs to persist data in the database and send a message to the Kafka

7
00:00:33,740 --> 00:00:35,570
for notifying other systems.

8
00:00:36,680 --> 00:00:43,520
If one of two these two operations fails, the data will be inconsistent data and these two systems

9
00:00:43,520 --> 00:00:45,200
become inconsistent.

10
00:00:46,060 --> 00:00:47,620
Here you can see the problems.

11
00:00:47,620 --> 00:00:54,580
This can lead to problems such as data loss or corruption, and can be difficult to resolve without

12
00:00:54,580 --> 00:00:57,850
proper error handling and recovery mechanism in place.

13
00:00:57,850 --> 00:01:02,020
So that means dual right can be hard to detect and fix.

14
00:01:04,769 --> 00:01:07,410
Here you can see an example of dual write problem.

15
00:01:07,410 --> 00:01:12,270
In this example we will illustrate create order use case in microservices.

16
00:01:12,270 --> 00:01:19,620
That means when create an order request comes, we want to change data in order database with creating

17
00:01:19,620 --> 00:01:24,420
a new record and also send an order created event to the event bus.

18
00:01:24,420 --> 00:01:31,380
Like Apache Kafka, both operation is handled with two different local transaction that causes dual

19
00:01:31,380 --> 00:01:32,430
write problems.

20
00:01:32,730 --> 00:01:38,070
As you can see the image we have a order microservices client application send the request which is

21
00:01:38,070 --> 00:01:43,110
the create order and in the order microservices we have two main operations.

22
00:01:43,110 --> 00:01:49,470
The first one is write order table which is the create any order item in the order table into the database,

23
00:01:49,470 --> 00:01:56,580
and after that order microservice is going to publish event to the create order event in order to start

24
00:01:56,580 --> 00:02:03,870
order fulfillment process to notify other microservices which subscribing to event from the create order

25
00:02:03,870 --> 00:02:07,950
event into the event path, which could be the inventory shipment and so on.

26
00:02:08,400 --> 00:02:10,410
So this is the dual write problem.

27
00:02:10,710 --> 00:02:16,170
So how to avoid dual write problem in microservices transactional outbox pattern.

28
00:02:16,290 --> 00:02:19,260
What is the transactional outbox pattern.

29
00:02:19,680 --> 00:02:23,310
The outbox pattern provides to publish events reliably.

30
00:02:24,060 --> 00:02:27,960
The idea of this approach is to have an outbox table.

31
00:02:27,960 --> 00:02:34,290
In the microservices databases, we solve dual write problem at the last video.

32
00:02:34,290 --> 00:02:39,480
That happens when application need to change data in two different systems.

33
00:02:40,260 --> 00:02:42,600
So we transactional outbox pattern.

34
00:02:42,600 --> 00:02:49,170
Instead of sending the data to separate locations, we send a single transaction that will store two

35
00:02:49,170 --> 00:02:51,900
separate copies of the data on the database.

36
00:02:52,800 --> 00:02:59,670
One copy is stored in the relevant database table, and the other copy is stored in an outbox table

37
00:02:59,670 --> 00:03:03,300
that will update the other microservices over the event path.

38
00:03:03,750 --> 00:03:11,040
For example, we might connect the outbox table from the Kafka or other messaging queue systems.

39
00:03:12,050 --> 00:03:17,810
That means when your API publishes event messages, it doesn't directly send them.

40
00:03:17,810 --> 00:03:21,980
Instead, the messages are persisted in a database table.

41
00:03:22,760 --> 00:03:28,940
After that, a job publish events to the message broker systems in the predefined time intervals.

42
00:03:29,900 --> 00:03:35,180
So with the outbox pattern, domain events aren't written directly to the event bus.

43
00:03:35,210 --> 00:03:41,990
Instead of that, it is written to a table in the artworks role of the service that stores the events

44
00:03:41,990 --> 00:03:43,850
in its own databases.

45
00:03:45,350 --> 00:03:51,920
However, the critical point is here that the transaction performed before the event and the event written

46
00:03:51,920 --> 00:03:55,190
to Outbox Table are part of the same transactions.

47
00:03:55,910 --> 00:04:02,900
For example, when an Eve order is added to the system, the process of the adding order and writing

48
00:04:02,900 --> 00:04:09,650
the order created event to the outbox table is done in the same transaction, in order to ensure that

49
00:04:09,650 --> 00:04:11,780
the event is saved to the database.

50
00:04:12,680 --> 00:04:18,769
If one of the process is failed, this will rollback the whole operation with following the Acid principles.

51
00:04:19,760 --> 00:04:26,600
The second step is to receive these events written to the outbox table by an independent service, and

52
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:28,460
write them into the event bus.

53
00:04:28,970 --> 00:04:31,130
We can see the image on the slide.

54
00:04:31,220 --> 00:04:38,090
This is an example of creating an order, creating new order record into the order table, and creating

55
00:04:38,090 --> 00:04:41,480
a new order created event into the outbox table.

56
00:04:42,230 --> 00:04:44,720
And these are the in the same transaction.

57
00:04:44,720 --> 00:04:48,320
And these same operations perform in the same transaction.

58
00:04:48,530 --> 00:04:54,620
If one of the process is fails, this will be rollback the whole transaction with following the Acid

59
00:04:54,620 --> 00:04:55,460
principles.

60
00:04:56,120 --> 00:04:58,520
After that, another service.

61
00:04:58,520 --> 00:05:04,730
Listen and post the outbox table records and publish to the into separate process.

62
00:05:04,730 --> 00:05:06,560
Publish the events into the event post.

